Appendix E – Road & Traffic Count Observation Report
The two mile corridor along Croft Road from Old Columbus Road to S.R. 4 is located northeast of the city of
Springfield within the vicinity of Buck Creek State Park. DLZ performed various field visits, including 8-hour
turning movement counts and 24-hour mechanical traffic counts, an inspection of the bridge over Buck
Creek, and a roadway analysis of the study corridor in order to determine the existing conditions and to
develop potential improvements along Croft Road.

The intersection of Croft Road/Home Road and S.R. 4 is a four-
legged signalized intersection. S.R. 4 has a lane configuration
consisting of a left-turn lane, a thru only lane, and a thru-right-
turn lane on both approaches. On S.R. 4, the northbound left-
turn storage lane length is 265 feet, while the southbound left-
turn storage lane length is 525 feet (S.R. 4 north and south of
the intersection drops to one travel lane in each direction).
The Croft Road and Home Road lane configuration consists of a
dedicated left-turn lane and a thru-right-turn lane on both

DLZ performed a site visit on April 25, 2014, in order to inspect the
existing condition of the bridge crossing Buck Creek (SFN 1239031).
See Appendix F for the bridge inspection report. There was significant
cracking and minor pavement damage near the ends of both approach
slabs, as well as potholes along the road centerline. Both approach
slabs showed signs of deterioration, with cracks and potholes as well.
There were signs of cracking along the top of the bridge deck, but
these cracks had been sealed. The deck slab was found to be spalled
with visible reinforcing at all four corners near the bridge abutments.
Along the south edge of the bridge deck, evidence of significant
spalling was seen caused by over-the-side drainage. The bridge
abutments showed cracking, with efflorescence on each face. There
was also minor cracking on the underside of the bridge deck.

page.text: There were 32 crashes between year 2010 and 2012 (3 years) within the project limits. The crash statistics
are summarized in Tables 1A-1H below. The crash data summary is located in Appendix D, which includes
Two main types of crashes accounted for 62 percent of all crashes within the study area. These were animal
crashes and rear-end crashes. Animal crashes accounted for 31% (10) of the total crashes. Nine (9) of the
animal crashes involved a collision with a deer, while the other crash involved a dog. Of these nine incidents
with deer, eight (8) of them occurred along Croft Road. Five (5) of the animal crashes occurred at night in
Rear-end crashes also accounted for 31% (10) of the total crashes. Rear-end crashes occurred when a vehicle
was slowing or stopped in traffic and the vehicle behind them was following too closely. Four (4) of these
crashes occurred at or near an intersection, with three (3) of them occurring at the intersection of Croft Road
and State Route 4. One (1) rear-end crash occurred when a vehicle was stopped, letting deer cross Croft
The fixed object crashes were the third highest crash type, with 16% (5) of the total crashes. Common causes
of fixed object crashes included failure to control the vehicle and excessive speeds. Three (3) of the fixed
object crashes occurred along Croft Road while the other two (2) occurred at the intersection of Croft Road
and State Route 4. Three (3) of the fixed object crashes, as well as the one (1) head-on collision, occurred
The two other types of crashes that occurred were left-turn crashes and angle crashes. Left-turn crashes
accounted for 12.5% (4) of all crashes while angle crashes accounted for 6% (2) of the total crashes. One of
the angle crashes was caused by a driver running a red light. The other crashes were a result of a driver’s
failure to yield. Three (3) left-turn crashes and one (1) angle crash occurred at the intersection of Croft Road
and State Route 4, while the other left-turn crash and angle crash occurred at the intersection of Croft Road
Of the 32 total crashes, 78% (25) were property damage only and 22% (7) resulted in injuries. There were no
fatalities in this section over the three year study period. Further analysis of the crash reports shows 25% (8)
of all crashes occurred under wet or snowy roadway conditions, with 19% (6) of all crashes occurring during
rain or snowy weather conditions. There were no crashes involving pedestrians or bicyclists.

DLZ also performed 24-hour mechanical traffic counts along Croft Road just north of Old Columbus Road and
just east of S.R. 4. This data was used to generate Average Daily Traffic (ADT) volumes, vehicle classification,
and speed. See Appendix A for traffic count data.
The ODOT Traffic Engineering Manual (TEM) and the Ohio Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices
(OMUTCD), which provide criteria and guidance for the installation of stop signs and traffic signals, were used
in order to perform an analysis for the following intersections as part of the Croft Road Corridor study:
The OMUTCD provides nine (9) individual signal warrants, where one or more should meet the minimum
requirements in order to justify a traffic signal installation. For this analysis, the first three warrants were
checked because these are the volume warrants. Using the traffic count data performed by DLZ, a signal
warrant analysis was compiled. The traffic signal warrant analysis was completed using PC Warrants
As part of the analysis, the posted speed limit of Croft Road (mainline) is 35 MPH. However, the posted
speed limit on Old Columbus Road is 40 MPH. Thus the 85% speed was taken to be greater than 40 MPH for
the warrant analysis at Croft and Old Columbus (70% volumes were used in the warrant analysis). The speed
limit on Robert Eastman Road was 35 MPH, so the 85% speed was less than 40 MPH and the 100% volumes
were used. The lane configuration at each intersection was entered as one lane. Right-turn Reduction
factors and Seasonal Adjustment Factors (obtained from ODOT) were also applied.
The intersection at Croft Road and Old Columbus Road did not meet any of the signal warrants. The
intersection only met two (2) of the required eight (8) hours of Warrant #1, and only met two (2) of the
required four (4) hours of Warrant #2. The intersection did experience volumes that exceed the minimum of
one (1) hour for the peak hour volumes of Warrant #3 (Peak Hour). However, this intersection does not
meet the criteria listed in the OMUTCD for Warrant #3. According to section 4C.04 of the OMUTCD, signal
Warrant # 3 “shall be applied only in unusual cases, such as office complexes, manufacturing plants, industrial

text.i: complexes, or high-occupancy vehicle facilities that attract and discharge large numbers of vehicles over a

page.text: short time.” Since the intersection does not meet the special circumstance criteria listed in the OMUTCD,
The intersection at Croft Road and Robert Eastman Road did not meet any signal warrants. The intersection
met zero (0) of the required eight (8) hours of Warrant #1, met zero (0) of the required four (4) hours of
Warrant #2, and did not exceed the minimum of one (1) hour for the peak hour volumes of Warrant #3.

page.text: Capacity is the volume of traffic that can pass through a roadway facility in a given amount of time
(vehicles/hour). The concept of Level of Service (LOS) is a qualitative measure of the operation of traffic flow.
LOS considers such factors as speed, travel time, freedom to maneuver, traffic interruptions, driver
inconvenience, safety, and delay. For different transportation facilities, the LOS is based on different
Signalized intersections are measured for average control delay in seconds per vehicle. Control delay
includes initial deceleration delay, queue move-up time, stopped delay, and final deceleration delay. The
delay measurement for vehicles at a signalized intersection is a combination of driver discomfort, driver
The LOS rating system as described in the 2010 Highway Capacity Manual gives a value of A through F to each
type of roadway facility representing best to worst traffic conditions. When designing roadway
improvements, it is desirable to accommodate peak hour volumes at a LOS C or D. Table 3 on the following
page summarizes the Levels of Service for signalized intersections. Table 4 on the following page summarizes
the Levels of Service for unsignalized intersections.

Existing peak hour analysis shows the intersection of Croft Road and State Route 4 operates at LOS B in the
AM and PM peak hours. During the AM peak hour the intersection delay is 12.6 seconds and during the PM
peak hour the intersection delay is 15.4 seconds. For each peak hour the westbound approach experiences
the worst delay at 14.7 seconds (LOS B) in the AM peak hour and 17.2 seconds (LOS B) in the PM peak hour.
Analysis of the unsignalized intersection of Croft Road and Old Columbus Road shows that the intersection
operates at LOS B during the AM peak hour and at LOS C during the PM peak hour.
Although the signalized intersection at Croft Road and State Route 4 operates at acceptable levels of service
throughout the day, an analysis was completed with optimized timings at this intersection. With optimized
timings, the intersection continues to operate at LOS B during the AM and PM peak hours (the optimized
timings results indicate minimal improvements in delay and are essentially the same as the existing timing
results; the existing timings are already optimized). Table 5 below and Table 6 on the following page
summarize the Levels of Service and Delays for the existing timings and the optimized timings. For complete
